 v2.0 did, we adopted them. this has made cosy_pak' b"smaller. thus brian evans' signal processing packages that supported" b'the laplacetransform and inverselaplacetransform functions in the' b'cosy_pak v0.81 are no longer needed directly by cosy_pak v0.9. for' b'power users who use signal processing we still recommend the use of the very' b'fine brian evans package on signal processing (available at' b'the anonymous ftp site gauss.eedsp.gatech.edu or ip on' b'the downside, the disadvantage of this update' b'can be that mathematica requires more runtime resources than its' b'previous version.' b'' b'' b'***********************************************************************' b'-- for mathematica users' b'' b'we have included the laplacetransform package from mathematica in' b"the directory `for_2.0'. please move all files and directory under for_2.0 into" b'the calculus directory under mathematica packages directory.' b'' b'**************************************************************************' b'' b'-- introduction' b'' b'this is an unsupported release of cosy_pak a control systems' b'analysis package for symbolic control systems analysis using' b'mathematica classical control systems analysis and design methods and some' b'modern control systems methods have been implemented in this package.' b'' b'this package and the attendant notebooks were developed on a' b'next (tm) computer (a unix based workstation). they have been' b'used as a supplementary teaching aid along with standard control' b'engineering texts (ogata phillips and harbor for' b"undergraduate courses in `control engineering i' taught at the systems" b'engineering department of cwru. in addition to the next, they have' b'also been tested successfully on apple macintosh computers (tm), and,' b"ibm pc's (tm) running ms windows(tm). we would be very much interested" b'to hear from you if you or anybody you know uses this software on' b'platforms not mentioned above. ibm users however will have to' b'evaluate the notebooks first to visualize the graphics.' b'' b'once installed (see below for instructions), this collection of' b'mathematica packages can be loaded by any user. bundled with the' b'packages are many notebooks ("cosy_notes") which demonstrate' b'the functionality of these packages. the notebooks follow a plan of' b'many fine, standard, undergraduate control engineering text books' b'listed in the references. examples used in these notebooks have' b'been collected from the various references given at the end of this' b'file. the contents of the notebooks in the "cosy_notes" directory are' b'given below.' b'' b'----------- begin "cosy_notes" contents b'' b'notebook file name: 01_introduction.ma' b'chapter introduction to control systems' b'' b'sections:' b'analyticity' b'poles and zeros' b'signals' b'forward laplace transforms' b'inverse laplace transforms' b'differential equation with zero-valued initial conditions' b'differential equation with initial conditions' b'' b'-----------' b'' b'notebook file name: 02_math_models.ma' b'chapter mathematical modeling of dynamic systems' b'' b'sections:' b'ode to state space' b'linearization of a nonlinear system of equations' b'state space to transfer function' b'' b'-----------' b'' b'notebook file name: 03_*_transient_response.ma' b'chapter transient-response analysis' b'(chapter split into three sub notebooks because of file' b'size)' b'' b'notebook file name: 03_1_transient_response.ma' b'' b'sections b'time response analysis' b'first order system' b'second order system' b'third order and higher order systems' b'' b'notebook file name: 03_2_transient_response.ma' b'' b'sections b'first order system (step response vs. time const)' b'' b'' b'notebook file name: 03_3_transient_response.ma' b'' b'sections b'second order system (step response vs. damping ratio)' b'' b'' b'-----------' b'' b'notebook file name: 04_steady_state_response.ma' b'chapter steady-state response' b'' b'sections:' b"routh's stability" b'steady-state error analysis' b'' b'-----------' b'' b'notebook file name: 05_root_locus.ma' b'chapter root-locus analysis' b'' b'-----------' b'' b'notebook file name: 06_freq_response.ma' b'chapter frequency-response analysis' b'' b'sections:' b'bode plot analysis' b'magnitude vs. phase plot (nichols plot)' b'polar plot' b'nyquist plot' b'combined example' b'' b'-----------' b'' b'notebook file name: 07_state_space.ma' b'chapter state space methods' b'' b'sections:' b'introduction' b'state transition matrix' b'controllability' b'observability' b'output controllability' b'pole placement design' b'observer design' b'time response using state space methods' b'' b'' b'----------- end notebook contents b'' b'' b'-- compressed files' b'' b'the files that contain a complete set of the cosy_pak v0.9' b'packages and notebooks for mathematica are:' b'' b'cosy_pak_09.tar.z \t\tcompressed tar file for unix systems' b'' b'cosy_pak_09.sit.hqx \tcompressed sit file for macintosh' b'systems and encoded by binhex b'format (requires the shareware' b'stuffit file v or higher).' b'' b'cosy_pak_ibm_09.zip \tzip file for the ibm pc running ms-dos' b'' b'once expanded the mathematica files can also be used on' b'macintosh ibm pc unix systems also.' b'' b'' b'-- installation of cosy_pak' b'' b'o in unix command line type the following command:' b'' b'zcat cosy_pak_09.tar.z tar xvf b'' b'o in macintosh open the .sit.hqx file using the shareware' b'stuffit v or higher.' b'' b'o in ibm command line type the following command:' b'' b'pkunzip -o -d cosy_pak_ibm_09.zip' b'' b'note: this .zip file was zipped by zip utility v2.0. you must use' b"pkunzip version or higher to unzip it. ibm pc's may limit the" b'directory name characters to eight. in that event type "pkunzip -o -d' b'cosy_pak.zip. you can also unzip the cosy_pak_ibm_09.zip file on any' b'unix machine if you have unzip utility on it.' b'' b'' b'uncompressing and untarring "cosy_pak_09.tar.z" or unzipping' b'"cosy_pak_ibm_09.zip" will create a directory called "cosy_pak".' b'' b'once the files are expanded you should see a single directory' b'"cosy_pak" containing the following three files, four' b'sub-directories and their contents:' b'' b'sub-directories in "cosy_pak":' b'cosypak contains control tool box packages' b'manual cosy_pak manual in .ps, .rtf, .txt, and .wn formats.' b'cosy_notes contains notebooks' b'for_2.0 contains laplace transform package from mathematica b'for mathematica users.' b'' b'files in directory "cosypak":' b'chap1.m chap2.m chap3.m chap4.m chap5.m chap6.m chap7.m' b'' b'files in directory "cosy_notes":' b'01_introduction.ma' b'02_math_model.ma' b'03_1_transient_response.ma' b'03_2_transient_response.ma' b'03_3_transient_response.ma' b'04_steady_state_response.ma' b'05_root_locus.ma' b'06_freq_response.ma' b'07_state_space.ma' b'' b'files in directory "for_2.0":' b'laplacetransform.m diracdelta.m' b'sub-directories in "cosy_pak":\tcommon' b'files in directory "common": support.m' b'' b'********************* important b'' b'the notebook example files(.ma files) will be under the' b'"cosy_notes" directory. to use the notebooks, move the directory `cosypak\' to' b'a' b'directory that mathematica can recognize b'' b'/locallibrary/mathematica/packages \ton a unix machine,' b'my_harddisk:mathematica:packages \ton an apple macintosh,' b'c:\\winmath\\packages \ton an ibm pc.' b'' b'at the beginning of the "initialization" cell of each notebook' b'in "cosy_notes" directory, we list the example about how to make' b'mathematica identify the directory:' b'' b'(* initialization of path b'' b'(* example for a unix machine (default) b'(*' b'$path=join[$path,' b'{"/locallibrary/mathematica/packages"}];' b'*)' b'' b'(* example for an apple macintosh b'(*' b'$path=join[$path,' b'{"my_harddisk:mathematica:packages"}];' b'*)' b'' b'(* example for ibm pc' b'*)' b'(*' b'$path=join[$path,' b'{"c:\\winmath\\packages"}];' b'*)' b'' b'change the pathname according to your machine by removing the' b"mathematica comment sign and before and after `$path'" b'setting.' b'' b'this command makes mathematica recognize the directory' b'' b'/locallibrary/mathematica/packages \ton a unix machine' b'my_harddisk:mathematica:packages \ton a apple macintosh' b'c:\\winmath\\packages \ton an ibm pc' b'' b'' b'-- mathematica users' b'' b'we include the laplacetransform package from mathematica in' b'the directory for_2.0. please move all files and directory under for_2.0' b'into the calculus directory under mathematica packages directory.' b'' b'' b'-- getting started' b'' b'after installation, start mathematica and open the notebooks in' b'the "cosy_notes" directory. all notebooks load their own packages.' b'navigate in the notebooks and enjoy. ibm users however will have to' b'evaluate the notebooks to visualize the graphics.' b'' b'***************************************************************' b'' b'-- user responsibilities' b'' b'we request you to take a few minutes and fill out the' b'information below and mail it to us by e-mail fax u.s. mail. this' b'will help us to keep your abreast of the improvements and release new' b'versions of cosy_pak. suggestions for improvements are welcome.' b'' b'-------------------------------cut here-------------------------------' b'' b'your name: b'' b'organization: b'' b'title: b'' b'e-mail: b'' b'postal address:________________________________________' b'' b'________________________________________' b'' b'comments b'' b'suggestions: b'' b'________________________________________' b'' b'' b'' b'' b'-------------------------------cut here-------------------------------' b'' b'mail this information to (e-mail fax u.s. mail) b'' b'' b'u.s. mail:' b'' b'prof. n. sreenath tel.: b'systems engg., crawford hall fax: b'case western reserve univ.' b'cleveland oh b'' b'***************************************************************' b'' b'-- report bugs' b'' b'please report bugs and leave comments to the address above.' b'any suggestion for